4. excussis omnibus: when all the evidence had been examined. —— et his . . . et his: appos. with omnibus. —— petit: sc. Augustus. —- sententiam: verdict. —ea omnium . . . quae Caesaris: if the votes were given orally, the other members of the council would be likely to agree with Caesar’s opinion. —codicilli: containing the verdict.—iuravit, etc.: it was so customary for childless persons to make the emperor their heir that Augustus feared he might be suspected of wanting Tarius to be childless. Suetonius (Auy. 66) speaks of Augustus's scrupulousness in accepting legacies.
